    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-03-03T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-03-03T04:00:00-05:00" n="226"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d226">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 European War 1939/2231: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador to the Yugoslav Government in Exile</hi>
                        (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Cairo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-03-03T11:00:00+02:00"
                            >March 3, 1944—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received March 5—8:02 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Yugos 55. The Department’s No. 6 Yugos of February 29, 8 p.m. My British
                    colleague advises me that the Commander in Chief, Mediterranean<note n="23"
                        xml:id="d226fn23">Lt. Gen. Sir Henry Maitland Wilson, Supreme Allied
                        Commander, Mediterranean Theater (SACMED).</note> is informed of this matter
                    and desires to be present or represented in the conversations and the Department
                    may therefore wish to instruct me whether his quality as an Allied commander
                    would be deemed sufficient to cover American military interest or whether as
                    instructed in the Department’s No. 21 [<hi rend="italic">1</hi>] January 5, 9
                    p.m. to the Legation in Cairo<note n="24" xml:id="d226fn24">Not printed.</note>
                    regarding similar contemplated discussions I should in addition ask the American
                    theater commander<note n="25" xml:id="d226fn25">Lt. Gen. Jacob L. Devers,
                        commanding general of North African Theater of Operations and Deputy Supreme
                        Allied Commander, Mediterranean.</note> to designate military advisory.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">MacVeagh</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
